<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910621-0031</DOCNO><DOCID>910621-0031.</DOCID><HL>   Developer in Texas   Linked to Failed Sandamp;Ls   Agrees to Plead Guilty</HL><DATE>06/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>COLORADO (CO)KENTUCKY (KY)NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   AUSTIN, Texas -- Texas real-estate developer Louis G.Reese III, who borrowed heavily from several now-failedthrifts, agreed to plead guilty to federal criminal chargesrelated to real-estate transactions with two Texas thrifts.   In exchange for the guilty pleas and Mr. Reese'scooperation in continuing investigations, federal prosecutorshave agreed not to pursue criminal charges relating to thedeveloper's dealings with other failed thrifts. Those thriftsinclude Silverado Banking, Savings andamp; Loan Association ofDenver, according to the plea agreement.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Reese agreed to plead guilty to a charge that heconspired to defraud federal thrift regulators through falsestatements in connection with three loans totaling $54million from the defunct Lamar Savings Association of Austin.The plea agreement, filed yesterday in federal court here,resolves other charges filed against Mr. Reese last year in afederal grand jury indictment.   In a separate case filed Wednesday in federal court inDallas, Mr. Reese was charged with conspiring to defraud theInternal Revenue Service of taxes on $14.2 million from thesale of a large Dallas property that was financed by thedefunct Western Savings Association of Dallas. The saleproceeds weren't reported to the IRS and were used topurchase land near Lexington, Ky., according to the chargeagainst Mr. Reese.   Mr. Reese is expected to plead guilty to both charges infederal court in Austin, possibly as early as July 1,according to attorneys in the case.</TEXT></DOC>